We recommended the Management to:

create a Committee which will be responsible for the registration of all real estate owned by the Municipality under the Torrens Title System pursuant to COA Circular No. 92-386; 

(b) upon completion of the land titling, require the Municipal Accountant to; 
i) prepare the necessary entries and record the cost incurred in the purchase or fair value if acquired through donation or transfers without cost of the land; 

 ii) record the lands with market value of ₱3,724,110.00 in its books after obtaining certified copy of the documents used in the titling of the said lands and ensuring that these are not identified or the same with any of the lands recorded in the books; and 

(c) direct the Municipal Engineer and Municipal Accountant to ensure that the Municipality has absolute or legal ownership over the properties before implementing the construction of buildings and other structures.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended that the Management:
direct the Municipal Accountant and the GSO to immediately reconcile their records to correct the reported balances of PPE at year-end and any discrepancies noted between their reports should be investigated and adjusted accordingly;
require the GSO and the Committee on Disposal to initiate the disposal process of the unserviceable properties following the procedures for the disposal of assets;
create an Appraisal Committee to compute and determine the proper value of the removed/replaced parts/materials that need to be derecognized in the books or use the cost of the replacement; and
d. 	require the Municipal Accountant to derecognize in the books, based on the report of the Appraisal Committee or the cost of the replacement, the costs of replaced/removed materials incident to the improvements, rehabilitations and renovations/repairs made.

The Audit Team recommended that the Management:

refrain from paying additional personal services cost such as COVID-19 Hazard Pay, in excess of the PS cap/limitation pursuant to Section 325 (a) of the RA No. 7160 and Section 7.0 of Budget Circular No. 2020-01;

require the Human Resource Management Officer (HRMO) and the Municipal Accountant to submit justification on the incomplete time in and out in the DTRs and inconsistencies noted in the DTRs attached in payroll of salaries and wages as compared to DTRs in the payment of COVID-19 hazard pay;

instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure the completeness of the supporting documents and propriety of the claims before processing the payments; 

require the HRMO to submit to this office a copy of the Schedule of AWA; and

strictly observe compliance with Budget Circular No. 2020-1 and other pertinent rules and regulations in the payment of COVID-19 Hazard Pay.

The Audit Team recommended that the Management:

allow the monetization only to those applicants who have accumulated fifteen (15) days of vacation leave credits provided that at least five days is retained after monetization;

allow the monetization of sick leave credits only if the applicant applies for monetization of fifty (50%) or more of all accumulated leave credits provided that vacation leave credits have already been exhausted, with valid and justifiable reasons and after obtaining favorable recommendation of the Local Chief Executive;

instruct the Municipal Accountant to strictly observe compliance to the provisions of Omnibus Rules on Leave particularly in the monetization of leave credits; and 

compel the Human Resource Management Officer to make the necessary adjustments of the leave balances as a result of erroneous charging of monetized leave credits from the balance of Sick Leave to Vacation Leave and submit the same to this Office for validation.

We reiterated our recommendations that the Management:

(a) take the necessary actions to expedite the collection of the unsettled disallowances;  

(b) subsequently, cause all the liable certifying and approving officers, who took part in the disbursement of disallowed expenditures, to assume responsibility in the final settlement of the remaining balance of the disallowance;  

c) We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant regularly submit a duly certified statement of settlement of disallowances to the Audit Team for reconciliation of unsettled balances per books and per SASDC;

d) ensure that before allowing settlement of disallowances through installment payment the same was authorized and approved by COA; and

e) instruct the Municipal Treasurer to exhaust all possible remedies to collect from each of the liable persons.

